Intro + Summary
Our ALG Project is a simulated Micromouse-style maze solver using SDL Plotter. Booth provides everything and our main job is to improve the logic inside DIRECTION nextMove(). Each time the driver asks for a move, our function must return a direction for the racer to move. 

We can use car->look(direction) to check whether there is a wall in that direction, and we should use that information to make smarter moves than the current random algorithm. Since we get three attempts on the same maze, the goal is to make the racer learn from earlier runs by storing information about the maze, then use that memory to perform better in later attempts.

Constraints / important details
	• The main algorithm is inside DIRECTION nextMove()
		○ I'm pretty sure we have to do all our work in this one function 
	• The starter algorithm is random: 
		○ It checks which directions do not have walls. 
		○ It adds those directions to a list. 
		○ It randomly chooses one safe direction. 
	• We get 3 attempts on the same maze. 
	• Static variables can be used to remember information between calls to nextMove() and between attempts. 
	• The goal is not just to finish, but to get the fastest possible run, because the best time out of the 3 attempts counts. 
	• Minimum requirement is to perform better than the provided random algorithm. 
	• If the mouse takes longer than around 2 minutes, Booth will kill the run. 

